lity comes from our taking on that theme in many other philosophical authors and literary genres. The philosophers include Aristotle (Ch. Horn) but also Cynics (S. Husson), Stoics (G. Reydams-Schils) and Cicero (S. McConnell). Other literary genres include comedic works from Aristophanes up to Lucian (G. Sissa; S. Kidd; N.I. Kuin) and history from Herodotus up to Diodorus Siculus (T. Lockwood; C. Atack; I. Sulimani). A last comparative chapter is devoted to utopias in Ancient China (D. Engels).  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aAntike. 4aChina. 4aGriechenland. 4aRömisches Reich. 4aUtopia. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aUtopia, ancient world, China.1 aAnnas, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAtack, Carol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDestrée, P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDestrée, Pierre, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEl Murr, Dimitri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEngels, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHatzistavrou, Antony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHorn, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHusson, Suzanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKidd, Stephen E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuin, Inger N.I., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLockwood, Thornton C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcConnell, Sean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOpsomer, J., econtributor.4